Lebanon's Comprehensive Crisis
Beirut — — When recalling, a typical financial crisis often seems to have signs beforehand; however, they rarely clearly indicate the direction of history.
Lebanon's situation is the same now, a predictable crisis has plunged the country into a highly unstable state.
Since Lebanon's long civil war (1975-1990) ended, its economy and political system have been sustained by external loans, which inevitably led to the continuous rise of public debt.
At a certain node, external capital inflow had to stop. This node has arrived at the end of 2019, and a series of negative impacts have occurred in succession.
This capital's "sudden stop" brought a severe triple crisis to the country.
The first problem is the current account.
Lebanon's current account deficit is as high as 25% of its GDP, with an export base that is too small to even afford necessary import commodity expenses.
The second problem is the fiscal one.
Lebanon's public debt now exceeds 150% of its GDP.
Government revenue is collapsing under the weight of economic decline, with a large budget deficit, already at 10% of GDP in 2019, and continuing to expand rapidly.
The most important thing is that Lebanon is also experiencing a banking crisis.
Main banks, as the main recipients of foreign capital inflows, have invested heavily in Lebanese sovereign debt (averaging 50% of their portfolio), and are now virtually insolvent.
These crises together are driving the Lebanese economy into a deep abyss.
Companies that are desperate for loans and imports have begun to lay off workers or shut down completely.
economic recession may lead to a Great Depression in Lebanon.
The main source of capital to support Lebanon's fragile political economy is not oil, but overseas Chinese, who are attracted to invest due to high interest rates and a fixed exchange rate pegged to the US dollar.
So, the symptoms of "Dutch disease" everywhere are not surprising: deposits have grown to over 400% of GDP, creating a wealth effect, and reducing the national savings rate to an unlikely level – 3% of GDP.
The degree of inequality is high and rising.
The real effective exchange rate appreciated by about 50% from 2000 to 2015, significantly weakening the tradable sector.
Due to the lack of exportable goods and services, Lebanon has been losing its educated youth.
But more importantly, large-scale capital inflows allowed sectarian elites to consolidate their status through patronage rather than merit.
These elites have milked the wealth of both the public and private sectors, establishing an obese clientelist ruling group.
Although this has ensured political stability in this originally chaotic region, it has failed to meet basic needs.
Even electricity supply is intermittent and unreliable, while the macroeconomic challenges it faces have not been addressed at all.
Financial crisis triggers a political uprising.
A mass revolutionary movement takes to the streets, opposing sectarianism and demanding an end to corruption.
Despite this, the government's response to Lebanon's economic problems has been overwhelmingly in favor of the elite, suggesting that this crisis may ultimately be "resolved" with the support of the poor and middle class, further consolidating sectarian politics.
For example, the state refused to introduce capital controls, allowing each bank's main shareholders, including ruling politicians, to decide how to withdraw cash in quantity.
In fact, this enables elites to transfer capital abroad, while ordinary citizens struggle to withdraw their deposits.
Furthermore, the central bank lowered the deposit interest rate, but has not yet lowered the interest rate on public debt, thus increasing bank profits.
Despite continuous decline in international reserves, Lebanon still continues to repay its major debt owed to domestic banks.
There are signs that it may start selling state assets to elite-related entities at fire-sale prices.
Meanwhile, the official exchange rate remains unchanged, with elites allowed to acquire US dollars at a lower exchange rate, while ordinary citizens face the reality of a rapidly depreciating exchange rate in the free market, with a 40% discount.
When the state starts printing lira to pay civil servant salaries, devaluation will accelerate.
Actually, the central bank has already been paying interest on US dollar deposits in lira (US dollar deposits account for more than 80% of all deposits) , thus creating conditions for inflation to offset public debt.
With the "lira-ization" of deposits through shareholder holdings pushing the cost of debt reduction to depositors, bank equity can basically be spared.
If this scenario becomes a reality, Lebanon's middle class will be greatly reduced due to the decrease in actual wages and pensions as well as the liquidation of savings.
The process of educated youth emigration will accelerate, and even the economic benefits of the immigrant community — which this system relies on — will be damaged.
If the sectarian system wants to survive under these conditions, it will rule over a poor population system, and this population system can be controlled by increasingly cheap shelters.
Ultimately, Lebanon will find itself in a similar situation to Venezuela.
On the other hand, the establishment of a new republic driven by revolution will take place in a completely different way.
Revolutionaries want to improve Lebanon, not abandon it.
They think its performance is far below its potential, and performance, elite management, and social justice should replace corruption, nepotism, and inequality.
They aim to build an energetic high-tech industry, make agriculture more sustainable environmentally, position the country as a cultural power station, and create more synergy with the immigrant community.
To achieve these goals, the reform movement hopes to seek orderly reduction of public debt, which will be guaranteed by bank equity, and to compulsorily reduce deposits of over 50% of the total deposits of the 1% deposit holders.
They support moderate currency devaluation and thorough improvement of the business environment to enhance export competitiveness.
They will seek deep fiscal restructuring, emphasizing the elimination of corrupt practices, and increasing social project and infrastructure expenditures.
With the support of the international community, including the International Monetary Fund (IMF), the inevitable recession will be alleviated.
The discord over the composition of the next Lebanese cabinet is a part of the larger struggle in the process of the country seeking new political solutions.
Financial crisis poses a fatal threat to the country; but it also presents an opportunity for political change.
The future of Lebanon hangs in the balance.
